label: Aristotle of Stagira
role: Philosopher, scientist, founder of Peripatetic school, systematizer of philosophy
description: Aristotle of Stagira is one of the most influential philosophers in Western history and the founder of the Peripatetic school. His work on voluntary action, deliberate choice, and moral responsibility in the Nicomachean Ethics (especially Book III) established the conceptual framework for virtually all subsequent ancient and medieval discussions of human agency and free will. Aristotle developed the critical distinctions between voluntary (ἑκούσιον) and involuntary (ἀκούσιον) action, introduced the concept of deliberate choice (προαίρεσις), and argued that 'what depends on us' (τὸ ἐφ' ἡμῖν) is real and grounds moral responsibility. In De Interpretatione 9, his famous 'sea battle' argument defends genuine contingency in the future against logical determinism, establishing that future contingent propositions need not be determinately true or false in advance. His Metaphysics (Book Theta) develops the metaphysical infrastructure of potentiality (δύναμις) and actuality (ἐνέργεια) that grounds his theory of real possibilities. Aristotle's work provided the philosophical vocabulary and conceptual distinctions that all later ancient schools—Stoics, Epicureans, Skeptics—had to engage with, whether to endorse, modify, or reject his views.

notes: Aristotle's influence on the free will debate is foundational. His conceptual framework—especially the voluntary/involuntary distinction, the notion of deliberate choice (prohairesis), and the defense of real contingency—shaped all subsequent ancient discussion. The Stoics, Epicureans, and later Peripatetics (especially Alexander of Aphrodisias) all defined their positions in relation to Aristotle's views.

label: Augustine of Hippo
role: Bishop, Doctor of the Church, Western Theological Giant
description: Most influential Western theologian whose thought on grace, free will, and predestination evolved dramatically from early optimism about liberum arbitrium to later doctrines of original sin, prevenient grace, and double predestination developed in anti-Pelagian controversy

label: Origen of Alexandria
description: Alexandrian theologian who developed radical doctrine of free will (autexousion) linked to pre-existence of souls and universal salvation (apokatastasis). Taught that all rational beings, including demons, will ultimately be saved through exercise of free will over cosmic time | Church Father and Christian theologian who engaged deeply with Greek philosophy. Defended free will (autexousion) against both Stoic determinism and Gnostic predestination. Argued that even the Devil has free will and that moral responsibility requires genuine freedom of choice.
key_positions: Radical free will (autexousion) - humans have power over their own will
Pre-existence of souls - souls existed before bodily birth
Apokatastasis - universal restoration/salvation of all beings
God does not compel against liberty of will
Free will explains why Jacob was loved and Esau hated before birth
Providence cares for immortal souls according to pre-existing merit
Paul addresses humans as having freedom of will and being cause of salvation or ruin

label: Alexander of Aphrodisias
role: Peripatetic philosopher, commentator on Aristotle, defender of libertarian incompatibilism
description: Alexander of Aphrodisias was the most important Aristotelian commentator of antiquity and the foremost ancient defender of libertarian incompatibilist free will. Appointed by the emperor as head of the Peripatetic school in Athens (c. 200 CE), Alexander produced systematic commentaries on Aristotle's works and original treatises developing Aristotelian philosophy against Stoic challenges. His De Fato (On Fate) is the definitive ancient statement of libertarian incompatibilism: the view that genuine free will is incompatible with causal determinism and requires real two-way power to do otherwise. Against Stoic compatibilism (which claimed fate and freedom are compatible), Alexander argued that Stoic determinism destroys 'what is in our power' (τὸ ἐφ' ἡμῖν), making deliberation pointless and responsibility impossible. Drawing on Aristotle's Metaphysics Theta (rational two-way powers), Nicomachean Ethics III (voluntary action and choice), and De Interpretatione 9 (contingency), Alexander constructed a systematic incompatibilist theory: humans possess genuine rational two-way powers that allow us to do or not do, choose A or B. These powers are not themselves causally determined but are sui generis sources of action. The actualization of a rational power in one direction rather than another has no sufficient prior cause - it is determined only by the agent's choice itself. This is agent causation: the agent as substance is the undetermined cause of determined effects. Alexander's arguments set the template for all later incompatibilist defenses of free will, from medieval scholastics to contemporary libertarians.

historical_importance: Alexander's incompatibilist arguments against Stoicism defined the free will problem for later philosophy. His agent-causal libertarianism influenced Duns Scotus, Thomas Reid, and contemporary libertarians.
